        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The Goodeniaceae apparently contradicted CD’s belief that all organic beings must occasionally cross-fertilise. He had referred to the problem in his ‘big book’ on species (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5799.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Natural selection</hi></ref>, pp. 63–4), explaining how the pollen and stigma in <hi rend="italic">Goodenia</hi> were completely enclosed by an indusium in the flower. He had subsequently studied the structure of the related genus <hi rend="italic">Leschenaultia</hi> (see letters to J. D. Hooker, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2716.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">[26 February or 4 March 1860]</ref>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2728.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">12 March [1860]</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2785.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">7 May [1860]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s observations and experiments on <hi rend="italic">Scaevola</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Leschenaultia</hi> are recorded in his Experimental book (DAR 157a). The observations described in the letter are dated 1 June 1860 (Experimental book, p. 64).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1225.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henrietta Emma Darwin</ref> had been ill since the end of April 1860.</note>
        </div>        
            
